.TH _PRINTF 3 "January 2025" "Holberton School" "Library Functions Manual"
.SH NAME
_printf \- formatted output conversion

.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
#include "main.h"
.br
int _printf(const char *format, ...);
.fi

.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf()
function produces formatted output on the standard output stream.
It interprets a format string and converts additional arguments
according to format specifiers introduced by the character '%'.

Ordinary characters in the format string are written as-is.
A '%' character introduces a conversion directive, which determines
how the corresponding argument is formatted and printed.

This implementation provides a minimal subset of the functionality
of the standard
.BR printf (3)
function and is intended for educational use.

.SH CONVERSION SPECIFIERS
The following conversion specifiers are supported:
.br

.TP
.B %c
The argument is treated as an
.I int
and printed as a single character.
.br

.TP
.B %s
The argument is a pointer to a null-terminated string.
If the pointer is NULL, the string "(null)" is printed.
.br

.TP
.B %%
Prints a literal percent sign.
.br

.TP
.B %d , %i
The argument is a signed integer.  The number is converted to
decimal notation and printed, including a leading minus sign
if negative.

.SH RETURN VALUE
Upon successful completion,
.B _printf()
returns the number of characters written.

If
.I format
is NULL or a conversion directive is incomplete
(for example, '%' at the end of the string),
the function returns -1.

.SH EXAMPLES
The following examples demonstrate typical usage:
.br
.EX
_printf("Hello %s!\\n", "Holberton");
.br
_printf("Value: %d\\n", 42);
.br
_printf("Percent: %%\\n");
.EE

